actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report and SVG samples.

This is actually a disposal-ordering issue in your code rather than a SkiaSharp bug. The closing `</svg>` tag is written by the Skia SVG device destructor, which runs when the `SKCanvas` returned by `SKSvgCanvas.Create` is disposed. With `using var`, all three objects (`managedStream`, `stream`, `canvas`) are disposed at the end of the enclosing block — but you're calling `managedStream.ToArray()` *before* that happens, so the canvas hasn't written the closing tag yet.

Here's the fix — use explicit `using` blocks to control when the canvas is disposed:

```csharp
var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using (var stream = new SKManagedWStream(managedStream))
using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, stream))
{
    // ... your draw operations here ...
}
// Canvas is now disposed — closing </svg> tag has been written
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();
```

This is also why `SKFileWStream` appeared to work — you likely read the file after the method returned (and all disposals completed).

The existing [test for SVG canvas](https://github.com/mono/SkiaSharp/blob/main/tests/Tests/SkiaSharp/SKCanvasTest.cs#L428-L466) demonstrates this pattern.
